===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|æfter|lang=ang}}, from {{proto|Germanic|after, *afteri|more aft, further behind|lang=en}}, from {{proto|Indo-European|apotero|further behind, further away|lang=en}} (note ''p'' → ''f'' shift), comparative form of {{proto|Indo-European|apo-|off, behind|lang=en|title=}}; see also {{proto|Indo-European|head=|h₂epo|off, away|lang=}}. Cognate with {{etyl|frr|-}} {{term|efter||after, behind|lang=frr}}, {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|achter||behind|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|After||anus|lang=de}}, {{etyl|non|-}} {{term|eftir|eptir|after|tr={{etyl|da|-}} & {{etyl|sv|-}} {{term|efter|lang=da}}|lang=non}}, {{etyl|no|-}} {{term|etter||after|lang=no}}. The [[Proto-Indo-European]] is the source of {{term|apo-||away, without|lang=en}}, from Ancient Greek {{term|ἀπό|tr=apo|lang=grc}}; comparative is also the source of Ancient Greek {{term|ἀπωτέρω||tr=apōterō|lang=grc}}.

